radiology.text:
INDICATION:  Pain, warmth and swelling at dialysis catheter site (femoral
catheter).  Evaluate for DVT.

COMPARISON:  None available.

TECHNIQUE:  Grayscale, color, and spectral Doppler ultrasound evaluation of
the left lower extremity was performed.

FINDINGS:

Normal color flow and respiratory variation is seen within bilateral common
femoral veins.  Left common femoral and proximal superficial femoral veins
demonstrate wall-to-wall color flow; however, due to patient's extreme
discomfort adequate compression could not be achieved.  Normal color flow,
compressibility, and augmentation is seen within mid and distal left
superficial femoral vein and left popliteal vein.  Evaluation of the calf
veins is limited.

IMPRESSION:

Suboptimal evaluation of the left common femoral and proximal left superficial
femoral veins; due to patient's extreme discomfort adequate compression could
not be achieved.  Otherwise, no evidence of deep venous thrombosis in the left
lower extremity. Calf veins not well seen.

Indication: Grossly infected left groin line

Physician: ___ MD, fellow, performed the procedure

Procedure: Tunnelled HD line removal

Details: The area was prepped and draped.  The line was removed intact with
gentle traction.  The tip was sent for culture, though likely contaminated by
pus in the tract.  Pressure was held for hemostasis.  A dressing was placed.

Conclusion:  Uncomplicated tunnelled HD line removal with tip culture.

INDICATION:  ___ woman with end-stage renal disease, on hemodialysis,
for tunneled hemodialysis line.  As there is no option for IJ lines, the line
had to be placed in the right common femoral vein.

OPERATORS:  Dr. ___ (fellow) and Dr. ___ (attending)
performed the procedure.

PROCEDURES PERFORMED:  Placement of right common femoral tunneled hemodialysis
line.

MEDICATION:  Sedation was achieved by providing divided doses of 1 mg of
midazolam.  Further pain management was provided by giving divided doses of
0.6 mg of Dilaudid.

PROCEDURE DETAILS:  Written informed consent was obtained from the patient. 
The patient was brought to the angiography suite and placed supine on the
imaging table.  A preprocedure timeout was performed as per ___ protocol.

Access to the right common femoral vein was obtained with ultrasound guidance
and use of the micropuncture technique.  ___ wire was advanced
into the right atrium and appropriate measurements taken for the line
selection.

Attention was now turned to creation of a subcutaneous tunnel.  Subsequent to
additional local anesthesia, a 1-cm skin incision was made inferior and
lateral to the venotomy site.  After providing generous lidocaine/epinephrine
anesthesia along the anticipated tunnel, a 15-cm tip-to-cuff hemodialysis
catheter was tunneled from the incision to the venotomy site with aid of a
metal tunneling device.  The venotomy tract was dilated using 6, 8, 10, 12,
and 14 ___ dilators.  Finally, a peel-away sheath was passed over the wire.
The wire and inner cannula were removed and the catheter was passed through
the peel-away sheath.  The peel-away sheath was peeled off while the catheter
was pushed into the right atrium.  This was confirmed with fluoroscopy,
demonstrating the catheter tip in the right atrium.  Both lumens withdrew
blood and flushed easily.  The catheter was secured with 0 silk sutures.  The
venotomy site was closed with ___ Vicryl subcuticular stitches.  Dry sterile
dressings were applied.  No immediate post-procedure complications were noted.
The patient tolerated the procedure well.

IMPRESSION:  Uncomplicated placement of 50-cm tip-to-cuff right common femoral
vein tunneled hemodialysis catheter.  The tip is located in the right atrium
and the catheter is ready for use.

INDICATION:  ___ female patient with AIDS and end-stage renal disease.
Recent placement of right groin tunneled hemodialysis line which was now found
to extend through a previously undiagnosed atrial septum defect into the left
atrium.  Questionable thrombus at catheter tip on initial US, now status post
anticoagulation with no thrombus appreciable on TOE.  Removal and exchange for
a shorter catheter requested.

OPERATORS:  Dr. ___ (fellow) and Dr. ___ (attending)
performed the procedure.

PROCEDURE PERFORMED:  Exchange of right common femoral vein tunneled
hemodialysis catheter for a shorter line.

MEDICATION:  Moderate sedation was achieved by providing divided doses of 1.5
mg of Dilaudid and 4 mg of midazolam.

PROCEDURE DETAILS:  Written informed consent was obtained from the patient. 
The patient was brought to the angiography suite and placed supine on the
imaging table.  A preprocedure timeout was performed as per ___ protocol. A
trans esophageal echo performed on the morning of the procedure did not
demonstate pericatheter thrombus.The procedure was performed under full
heparin anticoagulation.

Initial scout image redemonstrated the indwelling tunneled right common
femoral vein line with the catheter tip projecting over the right atrium. 
There was no evidence of interval dislocation or migration.  The sutures of
the line were cut and the latter then carefully withdrawn into the IVC. 
Subsequently, a stiff Glidewire was inserted through one of the line lumina
and the latter then exchanged for a 36 cm HD catheter via the existing tract. 
In the setting of anticoagulation, an 0 silk pursestring was placed around the
tract to act as apursedtring to aid hemostasis.  The catheter was further
secured by 0 silk sutures and a Tegaderm device.  Both lumina flushed and
aspirated easily.The line was primed with heparin as per protocol

An orientating neurological exam following the procedure was unremarkable.

IMPRESSION:  Uncomplicated exchange of a 50cm right common femoral tunneled
hemodialysis catheter for a shorter 36cm 15.5F dual lumen HD catheter via the
existing access.  The catheter tip is now in the upper IVC and the line is
ready for use.
